# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-eventbridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-eventbridge/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] These events may be happening across the various layers of an organization as sales leads, orders or customer service calls.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Or, they may be news items, text messages, social media posts, business processes (such as supply chain), traffic reports, weather reports, or other kinds of data.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] An event may also be defined as a "change of state," when a measurement exceeds a predefined threshold of time, temperature, or other value.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Analysts have suggested that CEP will give organizations a new way to analyze patterns in real-time and help the business side communicate better with IT and service departments.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] CEP has since become an enabling technology in many systems that are used to take immediate action in response to incoming streams of events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Applications are now to be found (2018) in many sectors of business including stock market trading systems, mobile devices, internet operations, fraud detection, the transportation industry, and governmental intelligence gathering.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The vast amount of information available about events is sometimes referred to as the event cloud.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] 2. the appearance of a man in a tuxedo with a woman in a flowing white gown.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] From these events the monitoring system may infer a *complex event*: a wedding.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] CEP as a technique helps discover complex events by analyzing and correlating other events: the bells, the man and woman in wedding attire and the rice flying through the air.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Commercial applications of CEP exist in variety of industries and include the detection of credit-card fraud, business activity monitoring, and security monitoring.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The CEP area has roots in discrete event simulation, the active database area and some programming languages.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The activity in the industry was preceded by a wave of research projects in the 1990s.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] According to the first project that paved the way to a generic CEP language and execution model was the Rapide project in Stanford University, directed by David Luckham.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In parallel there have been two other research projects: Infospheres in California Institute of Technology, directed by K.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Mani Chandy, and Apama in University of Cambridge directed by John Bates.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The commercial products were dependents of the concepts developed in these and some later research projects.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Community efforts started in a series of event processing symposia organized by the Event Processing Technical Society, and later by the ACM DEBS conference series.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] One of the community efforts was to produce the event processing manifesto.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] CEP is used in operational intelligence (OI) products to provide insight into business operations by running query analysis against live feeds and event data.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] OI collects real-time data and correlates against historical data to provide insight and analysis.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Multiple sources of data can be combined to provide a common operating picture that uses current information.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In network management, systems management, application management and service management, people usually refer instead to event correlation.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] As CEP engines, event correlation engines (*event correlators*) analyze a mass of events, pinpoint the most significant ones, and trigger actions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] However, most of them do not produce new inferred events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Instead, they relate high-level events with low-level events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Inference engines, e.g., rule-based reasoning engines, typically produce inferred information in artificial intelligence.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] However, they do not usually produce new information in the form of complex (i.e., inferred) events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] A more systemic example of CEP involves a car, some sensors and various events and reactions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Imagine that a car has several sensors—one that measures tire pressure, one that measures speed, and one that detects if someone sits on a seat or leaves a seat.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In the first situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires moves from 45 psi to 41 psi over 15 minutes.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] As the pressure in the tire is decreasing, a series of events containing the tire pressure is generated.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In addition, a series of events containing the speed of the car is generated.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The car's Event Processor may detect a situation whereby a loss of tire pressure over a relatively long period of time results in the creation of the "lossOfTirePressure" event.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] This new event may trigger a reaction process to note the pressure loss into the car's maintenance log, and alert the driver via the car's portal that the tire pressure has reduced.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In the second situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires drops from 45 psi to 20 psi in 5 seconds.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] A different situation is detected—perhaps because the loss of pressure occurred over a shorter period of time, or perhaps because the difference in values between each event were larger than a predefined limit.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The different situation results in a new event "blowOutTire" being generated.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] This new event triggers a different reaction process to immediately alert the driver and to initiate onboard computer routines to assist the driver in bringing the car to a stop without losing control through skidding.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] In addition, events that represent detected situations can also be combined with other events in order to detect more complex situations.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] For example, in the final situation the car is moving normally and suffers a blown tire which results in the car leaving the road and striking a tree, and the driver is thrown from the car.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] A series of different situations are rapidly detected.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The combination of "blowOutTire", "zeroSpeed" and "driverLeftSeat" within a very short period of time results in a new situation being detected: "occupantThrownAccident".
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Even though there is no direct measurement that can determine conclusively that the driver was thrown, or that there was an accident, the combination of events allows the situation to be detected and a new event to be created to signify the detected situation.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] This is the essence of a complex (or composite) event.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] It is complex because one cannot directly detect the situation; one has to infer or deduce that the situation has occurred from a combination of other events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] A natural fit for CEP has been with business process management (BPM).
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] BPM focuses on end-to-end business processes, in order to continuously optimize and align for its operational environment.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] However, the optimization of a business does not rely solely upon its individual, end-to-end processes.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Seemingly disparate processes can affect each other significantly.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Consider this scenario: In the aerospace industry, it is good practice to monitor breakdowns of vehicles to look for trends (determine potential weaknesses in manufacturing processes, material, etc.).
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Another separate process monitors current operational vehicles' life cycles and decommissions them when appropriate.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The integration of CEP and BPM must exist at two levels, both at the business awareness level (users must understand the potential holistic benefits of their individual processes) and also at the technological level (there needs to be a method by which CEP can interact with BPM implementation).
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] For a recent state of the art review on the integration of CEP with BPM, which is frequently labeled as Event-Driven Business Process Management, refer to.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Computation-oriented CEP's role can arguably be seen to overlap with Business Rule technology.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] For example, customer service centers are using CEP for click-stream analysis and customer experience management.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] CEP software can factor real-time information about millions of events (clicks or other interactions) per second into business intelligence and other decision-support applications.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] These "recommendation applications" help agents provide personalized service based on each customer's experience.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The CEP application may collect data about what customers on the phone are currently doing, or how they have recently interacted with the company in other various channels, including in-branch, or on the Web via self-service features, instant messaging and email.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The application then analyzes the total customer experience and recommends scripts or next steps that guide the agent on the phone, and hopefully keep the customer happy.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] A time series database is a software system that is optimized for the handling of data organized by time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Time series are finite or infinite sequences of data items, where each item has an associated timestamp and the sequence of timestamps is non-decreasing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Elements of a time series are often called ticks.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The timestamps are not required to be ascending (merely non-decreasing) because in practice the time resolution of some systems such as financial data sources can be quite low (milliseconds, microseconds or even nanoseconds), so consecutive events may carry equal timestamps.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Time series data provides a historical context to the analysis typically associated with complex event processing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] This can apply to any vertical industry such as finance and cooperatively with other technologies such as BPM.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The ideal case for CEP analysis is to view historical time series and real-time streaming data as a single time continuum.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] What happened yesterday, last week or last month is simply an extension of what is occurring today and what may occur in the future.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] An example may involve comparing current market volumes to historic volumes, prices and volatility for trade execution logic.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Or the need to act upon live market prices may involve comparisons to benchmarks that include sector and index movements, whose intra-day and historic trends gauge volatility and smooth outliers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Complex event processing is a key enabler in Internet of things (IoT) settings and smart cyber-physical systems (CPS) as well.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Processing dense and heterogeneous streams from various sensors and matching patterns against those streams is a typical task in such cases.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] The majority of these techniques rely on the fact that representing the IoT system's state and its changes is more efficient in the form of a data stream, instead of having a static, materialized model.
[src:aws-eventbridge/complex-event-processing] Reasoning over such stream-based models fundamentally differs from traditional reasoning techniques and typically require the combination of model transformations and CEP.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An *event* can be defined as "a significant change in state".
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] For example, when a consumer purchases a car, the car's state changes from "for sale" to "sold".
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] A car dealer's system architecture may treat this state change as an event whose occurrence can be made known to other applications within the architecture.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] From a formal perspective, what is produced, published, propagated, detected or consumed is a (typically asynchronous) message called the event notification, and not the event itself, which is the state change that triggered the message emission.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] However, the term *event* is often used metonymically to denote the notification message itself, which may lead to some confusion.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This is due to Event-driven architectures often being designed atop **message-driven architectures**, where such a communication pattern requires one of the inputs to be text-only, the message, to differentiate how each communication should be handled.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This architectural pattern may be applied by the design and implementation of applications and systems that transmit events among loosely coupled software components and services.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven system typically consists of event emitters (or agents), event consumers (or sinks), and event channels.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Emitters have the responsibility to detect, gather, and transfer events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An Event Emitter does not know the consumers of the event, it does not even know if a consumer exists, and in case it exists, it does not know how the event is used or further processed.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Sinks have the responsibility of applying a reaction as soon as an event is presented.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The reaction might or might not be completely provided by the sink itself.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] For instance, the sink might just have the responsibility to filter, transform and forward the event to another component or it might provide a self-contained reaction to such an event.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event channels are conduits in which events are transmitted from event emitters to event consumers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The knowledge of the correct distribution of events is exclusively present within the event channel.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The physical implementation of event channels can be based on traditional components such as message-oriented middleware or point-to-point communication which might require a more appropriate transactional executive framework.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Building systems around an event-driven architecture simplifies horizontal scalability in distributed computing models and makes them more resilient to failure.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This is because application state can be copied across multiple parallel snapshots for high-availability.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] New events can be initiated anywhere, but more importantly propagate across the network of data stores updating each as they arrive.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Adding extra nodes becomes trivial as well: you can simply take a copy of the application state, feed it a stream of events and run with it.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architecture can complement service-oriented architecture (SOA) because services can be activated by triggers fired on incoming events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This paradigm is particularly useful whenever the sink does not provide any self-contained executive.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] SOA 2.0 evolves the implications SOA and EDA architectures provide to a richer, more robust level by leveraging previously unknown causal relationships to form a new event pattern.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This new business intelligence pattern triggers further autonomous human or automated processing that adds exponential value to the enterprise by injecting value-added information into the recognized pattern which could not have been achieved previously.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture has two primary topologies.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] With “broker topology”, components broadcast events to the entire system without any orchestrator.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides higher performance and scalability.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] With “mediator topology”, there is a central orchestrator which controls workflow of events.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides better control and error handling capabilities.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] You can also use a hybrid model and combine these two topologies.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] There are different types of events in EDA, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An event can be made of two parts, the event header and the event body also known as event payload.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The event header might include information such as event name, time stamp for the event, and type of event.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The event payload provides the details of the state change detected.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An event body should not be confused with the pattern or the logic that may be applied in reaction to the occurrence of the event itself.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This method involves including only keys or IDs, allowing consumers to fetch the required data from external data sources, such as databases.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] While this approach is less scalable and slower due to the need for database queries, it minimizes bandwidth usage and reduces coupling issues.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] These methods represent two ends of a spectrum rather than binary choices.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Architects must carefully size the event payloads to meet the specific needs of event consumers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] In event driven architectures, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The first logical layer is the event producer, which senses a fact and represents that fact as an event message.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] As an example, an event producer could be an email client, an E-commerce system, a monitoring agent or some type of physical sensor.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Converting the data collected from such a diverse set of data sources to a single standardized form of data for evaluation is a significant task in the design and implementation of this first logical layer.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] However, considering that an event is a strongly declarative frame, any informational operations can be easily applied, thus eliminating the need for a high level of standardization.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An event channel is a mechanism of propagating the information collected from an event generator to the event engine or sink.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This could be a TCP/IP connection, or any type of an input file (flat, XML format, e-mail, etc.).
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Several event channels can be opened at the same time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Usually, because the event processing engine has to process them in near real time, the event channels will be read asynchronously.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The events are stored in a queue, waiting to be processed later by the event processing engine.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The event processing engine is the logical layer responsible for identifying an event, and then selecting and executing the appropriate reaction.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] It can also trigger a number of assertions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] For example, if the event that comes into the event processing engine is a product ID low in stock, this may trigger reactions such as “Order product ID” and “Notify personnel”.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This is the logical layer where the consequences of the event are shown.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This can be done in many different ways and forms; e.g., an email is sent to someone and an application may display some kind of warning on the screen.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Depending on the level of automation provided by the sink (event processing engine) the downstream activity might not be required.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] There are three general styles of event processing: simple, stream, and complex.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The three styles are often used together in a mature event-driven architecture.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing concerns events that are directly related to specific, measurable changes of condition.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] In simple event processing, a notable event happens which initiates downstream action(s).
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of work, thereby reducing lag time and cost.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] For example, simple events can be created by a sensor detecting changes in tire pressures or ambient temperature.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The car's tire incorrect pressure will generate a simple event from the sensor that will trigger a yellow light advising the driver about the state of a tire.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] In event stream processing (ESP), both ordinary and notable events happen.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Ordinary events (orders, RFID transmissions) are screened for notability and streamed to information subscribers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event stream processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of information in and around the enterprise, which enables in-time decision making.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing (CEP) allows patterns of simple and ordinary events to be considered to infer that a complex event has occurred.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing evaluates a confluence of events and then takes action.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The events (notable or ordinary) may cross event types and occur over a long period of time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The event correlation may be causal, temporal, or spatial.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] CEP requires the employment of sophisticated event interpreters, event pattern definition and matching, and correlation techniques.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] CEP is commonly used to detect and respond to business anomalies, threats, and opportunities.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Online event processing (OLEP) uses asynchronous distributed event logs to process complex events and manage persistent data.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] OLEP allows reliably composing related events of a complex scenario across heterogeneous systems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] It thereby enables very flexible distribution patterns with high scalability and offers strong consistency.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] However, it cannot guarantee upper bounds on processing time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven architecture is extremely loosely coupled and well distributed.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The great distribution of this architecture exists because an event can be almost anything and exist almost anywhere.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The architecture is extremely loosely coupled because the event itself doesn't know about the consequences of its cause. e.g.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] If we have an alarm system that records information when the front door opens, the door itself doesn't know that the alarm system will add information when the door opens, just that the door has been opened.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architectures have loose coupling within space, time and synchronization, providing a scalable infrastructure for information exchange and distributed workflows.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] However, event-architectures are tightly coupled, via event subscriptions and patterns, to the semantics of the underlying event schema and values.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] The high degree of semantic heterogeneity of events in large and open deployments such as smart cities and the sensor web makes it difficult to develop and maintain event-based systems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] In order to address semantic coupling within event-based systems the use of approximate semantic matching of events is an active area of research.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture is susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Finding the right balance in the number of events can be quite difficult.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Generating too many detailed events can overwhelm the system, making it hard to analyze the overall event flow effectively.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This challenge becomes even greater when rollbacks are required.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Conversely, if events are overly consolidated, it can lead to unnecessary processing and responses from event consumers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] To achieve an optimal balance, Mark Richards recommends to consider the impact of each event and whether consumers need to review the event payloads to determine their actions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] For instance, in a compliance check scenario, it may be adequate to publish just two types of events: compliant and non-compliant.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] This method ensures that each event is only processed by the relevant consumers, reducing unnecessary workload.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] One of the challenges of using event driven architecture is error handling.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] One way to address this issue is to use a separate error-handler processor.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] So, when the event consumer experiences an error, it immediately and asynchronously sends the erroneous event to the error-handler processor and moves on.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Error-handler processor tries to fix the error and sends the event back to the original channel.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] But if the error-handler processor fails, then it can send the erroneous event to an administrator for further inspection.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Note that if you use an error-handler processor, erroneous events will be processed out of sequence when they are resubmitted.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] Another challenge of using event driven architecture is data loss.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] If any of the components crashes before successfully processing and handing over the event to its next component, then the event is dropped and never makes it into the final destination.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] To minimize the chance of data loss, you can persist in-transit events and remove / dequeue the events only when the next component has acknowledged the receipt of the event.
[src:aws-eventbridge/event-driven-architecture] These features are usually known as "client acknowledge mode" and "last participant support".
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:aws-eventbridge/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-eventbridge/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
